prompt_template:
Create a {ASPECT_RATIO} image in the "Halftone Assemblage Metaphor PSA Poster Style" visual style.

Subject: {SUBJECT}
Action: {SUBJECT_ACTION}
Prop/Product: {PRODUCT_OR_PROP}
Location: {LOCATION}
Background: {BACKGROUND_ELEMENTS}
Main text: {MAIN_TEXT}
Secondary text: {SECONDARY_TEXT}
Accent symbol: {ACCENT_SYMBOL}
Wardrobe/styling: {WARDROBE_STYLE}
Style fidelity anchors: {STYLE_FIDELITY_ANCHORS}
Source content to avoid: {SOURCE_CONTENT_TO_AVOID}

Apply these style rules:
- Core metaphor: one visible source material category must be assembled into a different recognizable target silhouette. The target silhouette should read first from a distance; the individual source pieces should become clear up close.
- Composition: one dominant assembled silhouette in the lower-middle or slightly right field, compact top-left headline, tiny bottom-center footer, and generous empty warm paper space.
- Typography: heavy condensed uppercase sans headline with navy words and a small number of saturated red emphasis words; tiny centered footer microcopy with simple abstract symbols.
- Color: aged cream paper ground, muted blue-green halftone subject ink, deep desaturated navy text, and campaign red accents only.
- Texture and lighting: coarse paper grain, visible halftone dot screen, faded offset-print registration softness, flat ambient light, soft teal grounding shadow, no glossy modern finish.
- Graphic elements: minimal symbol row and small campaign imprint only; no dense decorative border, no stickers, no brand marks.

Avoid: random piles that do not form a silhouette, photorealistic product photography, glossy 3D render, modern vector flat design, dense collage, cinematic shadows, saturated rainbow palette, plastic bottle animal, pet story, recycle-icon copy, brand logos, watermarks, QR codes, social UI, long paragraphs, readable copied source slogans.

Important content rule: match the reference style first, then change the source content. Preserve the material-to-silhouette symbolic mechanism, while using new source materials, new target silhouettes, new text, and no literal source content.
